-    GXSetVtxAttrFmt(GX_VA_TEX0, GX_VA_TEX0, GX_TEX_ST, GX_F32, 0);
+    /* Real, unpatched original decomp bug (not a decompilation error --
+     * this exact typo shape, reusing the same GXAttr identifier for both
+     * arguments instead of the GXVtxFmt slot selector the first parameter
+     * actually wants, is a classic copy-paste mistake): every OTHER
+     * GXSetVtxAttrFmt call in this same function correctly passes
+     * GX_VTXFMT0 as the first (GXVtxFmt) argument; this one instead
+     * passes GX_VA_TEX0 (a GXAttr enumerator, value 13) where GX_VTXFMT0
+     * (0) belongs. Real hardware's own GX has no vtxfmt bounds check at
+     * all (it just computes a VAT register offset from whatever value
+     * it's given), so this silently sets up the wrong-but-not-fatal
+     * vertex-attribute-format slot on real hardware -- a genuine, latent
+     * rendering bug in the original game that nobody ever needed to
+     * notice. Aurora's own GXSetVtxAttrFmt DOES validate and FATALs
+     * outright ("invalid vtxfmt 13"), caught directly the first time any
+     * window actually gets drawn through this hook (HuSpr3DDisp, the
+     * sprite "3D warp/page-flip" hook3D effect registered on every
+     * window's sprite 0). Fixed to the value every neighboring call site
+     * already establishes as correct; the other arguments are unchanged
+     * (GX_VA_TEX0 is exactly right there -- it says WHICH attribute this
+     * call configures, a completely different, correct use of the same
+     * enumerator). */
+    GXSetVtxAttrFmt(GX_VTXFMT0, GX_VA_TEX0, GX_TEX_ST, GX_F32, 0);
@@ -562,0 +680,30 @@
+    /* Real, unpatched original decomp gap (same class as game/hsfman.c's
+     * Hu3DZClear): this function's own GXBegin(GX_QUADS, GX_VTXFMT0,
+     * col*row*4) is followed by a loop that emits EXACTLY col*row*4
+     * vertices, so on real hardware -- whose GX FIFO ends a primitive
+     * purely by vertex count, not an explicit End signal -- this was
+     * always complete and correct with no GXEnd() call at all. Patched
+     * here (unlike Hu3DZClear, left as bridge-side-tolerated) because THIS
+     * specific gap has a real, confirmed downstream consequence the
+     * general bridge fix can't safely paper over: HuSpr3DDisp is a sprite
+     * hook3D callback, called from HuSprDisp's own per-layer loop -- an
+     * arbitrary amount of OTHER code can run between this function's own
+     * last vertex and whatever the NEXT real GXBegin happens to be, and
+     * the bridge's generic "auto-close on the next GXBegin" tolerance has
+     * no way to know this function's own primitive was already, correctly,
+     * complete well before that point. Caught directly (Aurora build):
+     * "GXEnd: vertex count mismatch: GXBegin declared 128 vertices (8B
+     * each, 1024B total) but 1075 bytes were written (134 vertices)" --
+     * extra bytes from whatever ran in the gap before the bridge's own
+     * auto-close finally fired. A real, explicit GXEnd() call here is a
+     * pure no-op on real hardware (zero behavior change there) while
+     * telling Aurora exactly where this primitive really ends, closing
+     * that gap at the source instead of relying on the bridge's
+     * necessarily-coarser fallback. */
+    GXEnd();
